WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.180 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:17.040 --> 00:00:18.340
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan:
Good afternoon.

00:00:18.340 --> 00:00:20.290
Welcome to the Library
of Congress.

00:00:20.290 --> 00:00:22.620
My name is Colleen Shogan,
and I'm the deputy director

00:00:22.620 --> 00:00:25.910
for National and International
Outreach here at the Library.

00:00:25.910 --> 00:00:28.520
We're the division responsible
for public programming,

00:00:28.520 --> 00:00:32.800
and the Kluge Center plays an
important role in that respect.

00:00:32.800 --> 00:00:35.150
We'll soon hear introductions
of our esteemed panel,

00:00:35.150 --> 00:00:37.670
but I'd like to take a
moment to briefly talk to you

00:00:37.670 --> 00:00:40.220
about the John W.
Kluge Center directed

00:00:40.220 --> 00:00:42.260
by Dr. John Haskell
who is on stage.

00:00:42.260 --> 00:00:45.720
It is our scholarly center
at the Library of Congress

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:48.660
but has a unique mission,
namely, bringing top minds

00:00:48.660 --> 00:00:51.720
to Capitol Hill with the
goal of informing Congress

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:54.300
and the larger Washington
D.C. community.

00:00:54.300 --> 00:00:57.610
In short, the Kluge Center
aims to bridge the division

00:00:57.610 --> 00:00:59.760
between knowledge and power.

00:00:59.760 --> 00:01:02.930
The Kluge Center supports
visiting scholars each year,

00:01:02.930 --> 00:01:05.550
both at the junior
and the senior levels.

00:01:05.550 --> 00:01:07.110
We want our residential scholars

00:01:07.110 --> 00:01:10.650
to utilize the Library's vast
collections and spend time

00:01:10.650 --> 00:01:13.720
with our knowledgeable
experts and curators.

00:01:13.720 --> 00:01:15.050
We also want our scholars

00:01:15.050 --> 00:01:17.730
to share their discoveries
and insights.

00:01:17.730 --> 00:01:20.810
The Kluge Center does that
through a variety of programming

00:01:20.810 --> 00:01:23.490
for the general public,
for members of Congress

00:01:23.490 --> 00:01:25.790
and for congressional staff.

00:01:25.790 --> 00:01:27.390
In that regard, I
would be remiss

00:01:27.390 --> 00:01:28.860
if I did not make you aware

00:01:28.860 --> 00:01:32.470
of some terrific Kluge
programming in the near future.

00:01:32.470 --> 00:01:36.410
Tomorrow, Dr. Bruce Jentleson,
a former Kluge Kissinger Chair,

00:01:36.410 --> 00:01:39.490
will discuss his new
book, The Peacemakers.

00:01:39.490 --> 00:01:42.060
That event will take
place in room 119

00:01:42.060 --> 00:01:45.340
of the Jefferson Building
just across the street.

00:01:45.340 --> 00:01:47.790
Additionally, there is a wide
variety of programs scheduled

00:01:47.790 --> 00:01:51.010
for the coming weeks
ranging from Italian opera

00:01:51.010 --> 00:01:53.610
to the Bible's role
in American history.

00:01:53.610 --> 00:01:57.310
Please check the Kluge Center
website for more information.

00:01:57.310 --> 00:02:00.210
Finally, we are proud to
cosponsor this event today

00:02:00.210 --> 00:02:02.090
with the University of Denver.

00:02:02.090 --> 00:02:06.060
I'd now like to welcome Dean
Daniel McIntosh to the stage

00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:09.750
who will provide introductory
remarks for our panel.

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:16.340
&gt;&gt; Daniel McIntosh:
Hi, I'm Danny McIntosh.

00:02:16.340 --> 00:02:18.130
I'm the dean of Arts,
Humanities and Social Sciences

00:02:18.130 --> 00:02:20.830
at the University of Denver,
and it is a real pleasure

00:02:20.830 --> 00:02:23.100
to be cohosting this
with the Kluge Center

00:02:23.100 --> 00:02:25.010
and the Library of Congress.

00:02:25.010 --> 00:02:28.690
The University of Denver is a
private university dedicated

00:02:28.690 --> 00:02:30.240
to the public good.

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:35.300
As such a university, we
hope to engage scholars

00:02:35.300 --> 00:02:38.880
and the community across the
nation and across the world.

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:42.000
We believe there should be no
barriers between scholarship

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:43.760
and practice, no barriers

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:45.930
between campus and
the community.

00:02:45.930 --> 00:02:49.410
Therefore, we encourage and we
support our students, faculty

00:02:49.410 --> 00:02:52.860
and staff to engage with
the wider communities

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:56.900
to share their scholarship
and to be in conversation

00:02:56.900 --> 00:02:58.920
with scholars, staff people

00:02:58.920 --> 00:03:01.450
and the community
across the country.

00:03:01.450 --> 00:03:04.850
We want to model this
integration not only in our work

00:03:04.850 --> 00:03:07.820
but also in our students'
experiences.

00:03:07.820 --> 00:03:11.310
From psychology students
who prepare research reports

00:03:11.310 --> 00:03:14.360
and plans for nonprofits
in the city of Denver

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:17.780
to religious study
students who work as interns

00:03:17.780 --> 00:03:20.530
in faith-based organizations
across the country.

00:03:20.530 --> 00:03:24.330
And from anthropology students
who work with rural Coloradans

00:03:24.330 --> 00:03:27.880
and Japanese-Americans
interpreting the events

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:32.860
and the remnants of the Amache
Internment Camp, our students go

00:03:32.860 --> 00:03:37.930
from the classroom to the field
to the lab understanding how

00:03:37.930 --> 00:03:42.270
to integrate and tie together
scholarship and application.

00:03:42.270 --> 00:03:44.150
One example of this
effort at the University

00:03:44.150 --> 00:03:47.060
of Denver is the Center
on American Politics.

00:03:47.060 --> 00:03:50.220
The Center on American
Politics is a new organization

00:03:50.220 --> 00:03:53.040
that is interdisciplinary
that ties together scholars

00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:56.260
from the law school, from arts,
humanities and social sciences,

00:03:56.260 --> 00:03:59.940
political science, sociology
and international studies,

00:03:59.940 --> 00:04:02.080
all working to understand
the very basis

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:03.950
of politics in America.

00:04:03.950 --> 00:04:06.540
Politics are the way that
people's voices are heard.

00:04:06.540 --> 00:04:09.270
It's important for us to
understand how this works.

00:04:09.270 --> 00:04:11.550
One of the speakers today
is Professor Seth Masket,

00:04:11.550 --> 00:04:14.480
professor in the Political
Science Department and director

00:04:14.480 --> 00:04:16.760
of our new Center on
American Politics.

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:19.900
We want to be part
of the conversation.

00:04:19.900 --> 00:04:23.920
We want to be a part of applying
our scholarship to issues

00:04:23.920 --> 00:04:26.810
that are important to critical
issues of the time, and as such,

00:04:26.810 --> 00:04:28.930
we are pleased to be
cosponsoring this even

00:04:28.930 --> 00:04:31.840
with the Kluge Center and
the Library of Congress.

00:04:31.840 --> 00:04:34.950
With that, I'd like to introduce
our moderator, John Haskell,

00:04:34.950 --> 00:04:36.280
who's the director of
the Kluge Center here

00:04:36.280 --> 00:04:37.820
at the Library of Congress.

00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:39.180
Thank you.

00:04:39.180 --> 00:04:40.480
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Thank
you, Dean McIntosh.

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:42.130
[ Applause ]

00:04:42.130 --> 00:04:46.840
And as Colleen pointed out a
minute ago, we're really happy

00:04:46.840 --> 00:04:49.360
to work with the
University of Denver

00:04:49.360 --> 00:04:51.960
because we're doing
what we both want to do,

00:04:51.960 --> 00:04:54.420
which was to bring our
scholars, to bring scholarship

00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:55.720
to the wider community.

00:04:55.720 --> 00:04:58.100
And in this particular
case, we have Seth

00:04:58.100 --> 00:04:59.650
and also two other scholars.

00:04:59.650 --> 00:05:04.120
And I'll say a couple of
other things about Seth

00:05:04.120 --> 00:05:05.420
that weren't mentioned.

00:05:05.420 --> 00:05:10.200
He's already, he is the
chair in American Law

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:12.050
and Governance here
at the Kluge Center.

00:05:12.050 --> 00:05:13.680
He just started in May,

00:05:13.680 --> 00:05:15.920
and he'll be here
through the summer.

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:19.780
And we have other
programming in mind for him.

00:05:19.780 --> 00:05:24.340
He is, as pointed out, the head
of the Center at the University

00:05:24.340 --> 00:05:25.930
and is very well-regarded.

00:05:25.930 --> 00:05:28.550
He is a classic of the kind
of scholar we try to bring

00:05:28.550 --> 00:05:31.980
to Kluge Center because not
only is he well-respected

00:05:31.980 --> 00:05:34.550
within the field, one of the
leaders within the field,

00:05:34.550 --> 00:05:38.290
speaking to other academics,
he's out there on 538 and a lot

00:05:38.290 --> 00:05:42.460
of other sites and writes
for a much larger audience.

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:45.450
Jennifer Victor is in
