&gt;&gt; Hi, thanks for coming out.

00:48:59.680 --> 00:49:01.220
So my question is
a bit reflective.

00:49:01.220 --> 00:49:06.110
When I was younger, I am older,
a lot older than what I look.

00:49:06.110 --> 00:49:09.380
So when I was younger, I did
ten years in the Marine Corps,

00:49:09.380 --> 00:49:12.040
so I always had this mindset
that you can pull yourself

00:49:12.040 --> 00:49:13.810
up by your bootstraps.

00:49:13.810 --> 00:49:17.250
Now that I'm 40 plus
and have two kids,

00:49:17.250 --> 00:49:22.700
one 17 and 15, I've
been a teacher.

00:49:22.700 --> 00:49:26.550
And I've seen that that is not
the case for African-Americans.

00:49:26.550 --> 00:49:30.960
So as I taught fourth grade,
teaching them the 13th,

00:49:30.960 --> 00:49:34.610
14th and 15th Amendments, and
especially that 14th Amendment

00:49:34.610 --> 00:49:38.270
about equality for
African-Americans.

00:49:38.270 --> 00:49:43.230
And we were discussing the
Brown versus Board of Education.

00:49:43.230 --> 00:49:45.500
And I've lived in
many states before,

00:49:45.500 --> 00:49:48.440
but then I started
reading and learning

00:49:48.440 --> 00:49:52.870
about how Virginia was able
to circumvent that Brown

00:49:52.870 --> 00:49:55.650
versus Board of Education
and how

00:49:55.650 --> 00:49:59.230
that still plays a part
today in our education system

00:49:59.230 --> 00:50:04.120
and how negatively it
impacts African-Americans.

00:50:04.120 --> 00:50:10.190
And I was talking to my husband
yesterday, and I was like,

00:50:10.190 --> 00:50:13.890
where could an African-American
mom, our family go

00:50:13.890 --> 00:50:18.220
to an African-American
community that is thriving?

00:50:18.220 --> 00:50:23.350
That you have doctors, lawyers,
hospitals that look like you,

00:50:23.350 --> 00:50:27.580
there's very few
places that you can go.

00:50:27.580 --> 00:50:31.890
And I asked him that question
because I spent a year

00:50:31.890 --> 00:50:37.920
as a teacher in a
very wealthy community

00:50:37.920 --> 00:50:39.450
where teachers did
not want to work

00:50:39.450 --> 00:50:41.340
with me simply because
of my color.

00:50:41.340 --> 00:50:44.210
That never happened to
me in the Marine Corps.

00:50:44.210 --> 00:50:46.750
And I can say well, thank God

00:50:46.750 --> 00:50:50.470
for all the African-Americans
that came before me.

00:50:50.470 --> 00:50:54.630
But why would I want to put
my kids through that ordeal?

00:50:54.630 --> 00:50:59.320
Why would they have to
endure that simply because,

00:50:59.320 --> 00:51:04.550
and then I don't, republican or
democratic, there's not enough

00:51:04.550 --> 00:51:07.860
of African-Americans
to make it a valid,

00:51:07.860 --> 00:51:10.550
that we have a valid say.

00:51:10.550 --> 00:51:14.220
So regardless of
what party is voting,

00:51:14.220 --> 00:51:19.800
when do we get past the
nationalism of isms?

00:51:19.800 --> 00:51:22.430
When do we get past
that and look

00:51:22.430 --> 00:51:24.060
at people for their humanity.

00:51:24.060 --> 00:51:27.480
Because we're spending
so much money making sure

00:51:27.480 --> 00:51:30.100
that other countries do it
right, but we don't do it right.

00:51:30.100 --> 00:51:33.520
And I can't send my kids, my
daughter graduates next year.

00:51:33.520 --> 00:51:38.000
I don't feel comfortable sending
her into a work environment

00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:42.430
that she has to endure
what I endured

00:51:42.430 --> 00:51:50.730
and am still enduring simply
because we raise communities

00:51:50.730 --> 00:51:54.550
to believe that we're one better
than the other because of isms.

00:51:54.550 --> 00:51:56.380
How do we address that?

00:51:56.380 --> 00:51:59.900
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: So I think one
of the ways we could maybe talk

00:51:59.900 --> 00:52:03.900
about that is to talk about
how is it that minorities,

00:52:03.900 --> 00:52:06.100
whether ethnic or racial
or other, you know,

00:52:06.100 --> 00:52:08.780
sexual orientation,
other minorities,

00:52:08.780 --> 00:52:10.940
how do they get influenced
within the party system?

00:52:10.940 --> 00:52:14.420
You know, what's a good
way to think about that?

00:52:14.420 --> 00:52:17.590
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Nicoll Victor: So
to me, part of what's going

00:52:17.590 --> 00:52:20.490
on in polarization in
American politics right now,

00:52:20.490 --> 00:52:21.790
and you're speaking primarily

00:52:21.790 --> 00:52:24.170
about the African-American
community, which is largely

00:52:24.170 --> 00:52:27.540
for the last 50 years or so
been kind of solidly married

00:52:27.540 --> 00:52:29.820
to the Democratic party.

00:52:29.820 --> 00:52:32.860
For, largely, I was going
to say for better or worse,

00:52:32.860 --> 00:52:38.650
but really it's for worse that
throughout American history,

00:52:38.650 --> 00:52:42.210
one party or the other has
essentially always kind of been,

00:52:42.210 --> 00:52:44.290
I don't want to put this
impolitely, but sort of married

00:52:44.290 --> 00:52:45.870
to the racist devil, right.

00:52:45.870 --> 00:52:49.060
So for lots of the 19th century
and into the 20th century,

00:52:49.060 --> 00:52:50.360
it was the democratic party.

00:52:50.360 --> 00:52:51.660
They were the party of slavery.

00:52:51.660 --> 00:52:54.320
They were the party that
controlled the South and fought

00:52:54.320 --> 00:52:56.710
to maintain slavery and
then ultimately lost.

00:52:56.710 --> 00:52:58.830
But then found various
institutions to kind

00:52:58.830 --> 00:53:00.950
of keep that culture going.

00:53:00.950 --> 00:53:03.380
Until you get to the middle
part of the 20th century,

00:53:03.380 --> 00:53:06.470
and the democratic party
reforms on that issue.

00:53:06.470 --> 00:53:10.300
And you get actors like John
F. Kennedy and LBJ and others

00:53:10.300 --> 00:53:12.370
who pick up the mantle
of civil rights.

00:53:12.370 --> 00:53:14.530
The African-American has sort

00:53:14.530 --> 00:53:16.700
of opportunistically
bringing this new portion

00:53:16.700 --> 00:53:18.960
of the electorate
into the party.

00:53:18.960 --> 00:53:20.260
They did that quite well.

00:53:20.260 --> 00:53:22.200
The republican party
responds and pivots

00:53:22.200 --> 00:53:25.320
by following what Nixon
called the southern strategy.

00:53:25.320 --> 00:53:28.510
And that sets off the
democratic and American

00:53:28.510 --> 00:53:32.970
and republican parties on their,
what is now their current path

00:53:32.970 --> 00:53:36.200
in which the democratic party
much more strongly holds the

00:53:36.200 --> 00:53:37.810
mantle of civil rights.

00:53:37.810 --> 00:53:42.090
And the republican party is
often the counter to that.

00:53:42.090 --> 00:53:46.810
And so part of what I think
perpetuates this and prevents us

00:53:46.810 --> 00:53:48.960
from getting beyond
it in some of the ways

00:53:48.960 --> 00:53:52.530
that you're expressing
is that as a country,

00:53:52.530 --> 00:53:55.100
we've never really
reconciled how

00:53:55.100 --> 00:53:58.950
to get beyond our
legacy of slavery.

00:53:58.950 --> 00:54:01.820
We've never done a very
good job as a country

00:54:01.820 --> 00:54:05.820
of showing complicity there and
showing some sense of contrition

00:54:05.820 --> 00:54:09.750
for the role that we played
in perpetuating that economy

00:54:09.750 --> 00:54:11.570
for hundreds of years.

00:54:11.570 --> 00:54:14.950
And it's now completely baked
into our political parties

00:54:14.950 --> 00:54:18.070
in ways that is divisive
rather than in ways

00:54:18.070 --> 00:54:19.440
that promote some
kind of healing.

00:54:19.440 --> 00:54:21.350
And lots of institutions
perpetuate this.

00:54:21.350 --> 00:54:23.840
I'm not just talking about
structural racism, but I mean,

00:54:23.840 --> 00:54:26.120
federalism itself, the
fact that we have states

00:54:26.120 --> 00:54:29.280
and United States Senate, like
all of these institutions were

00:54:29.280 --> 00:54:33.220
in some ways created
to perpetuate slavery.

00:54:33.220 --> 00:54:36.930
And our inability to
overcome that issue

00:54:36.930 --> 00:54:40.170
and to really fully
reconcile with it as a country

00:54:40.170 --> 00:54:42.680
and as a people I think
has it much more baked

00:54:42.680 --> 00:54:45.770
into our politics in ways
that are really difficult

00:54:45.770 --> 00:54:48.710
to reconcile at this point
until we get political actors

00:54:48.710 --> 00:54:51.660
who decide they want
to try to address that.

00:54:51.660 --> 00:54:56.600
So I often think about in the
post-Nazi period in Germany,

00:54:56.600 --> 00:55:00.610
you can't go into a town village
or hamlet in all of Germany

00:55:00.610 --> 00:55:04.820
without finding some memorial
somewhere to the Holocaust.

00:55:04.820 --> 00:55:06.570
It's a part of the
national identity.

00:55:06.570 --> 00:55:08.560
It's a part of the
national culture

00:55:08.560 --> 00:55:11.980
to show some national contrition

00:55:11.980 --> 00:55:13.690
for their participation
in that genocide.

00:55:13.690 --> 00:55:15.950
And the Americans never
done that with slavery.

00:55:15.950 --> 00:55:20.210
And I think that affects the
way our partisan politics deals

00:55:20.210 --> 00:55:22.490
with that issue even today.

