00:59:15.280 --> 00:59:18.320
as running either their personal
offices or their committees

00:59:18.320 --> 00:59:19.920
or whatever position
it is that they have.

00:59:19.920 --> 00:59:22.790
And I'm thinking of
members of Congress.

00:59:22.790 --> 00:59:26.350
And so it could be that
there are more subtle forms

00:59:26.350 --> 00:59:30.300
of negotiation or
management or politicking

00:59:30.300 --> 00:59:35.100
that changes operations at a
level that's more difficult

00:59:35.100 --> 00:59:36.690
for scholars like us to observe.

00:59:36.690 --> 00:59:39.080
Except perhaps in the long run.

00:59:39.080 --> 00:59:41.480
So I guess I'm of
mixed mind about this.

00:59:41.480 --> 00:59:44.620
On the one hand, I think
creating a Congress

00:59:44.620 --> 00:59:46.910
that looks more like
America is a good thing.

00:59:46.910 --> 00:59:51.820
We know that there are huge
advantages to having some level

00:59:51.820 --> 00:59:54.570
of descriptive representation.

00:59:54.570 --> 00:59:56.220
Whether that's race
or gender or whatever.

00:59:56.220 --> 01:00:00.120
On the other hand, we also know
that once a minority group,

01:00:00.120 --> 01:00:03.270
whether you're talking about
race or women or whatever,

01:00:03.270 --> 01:00:06.240
come into office, and they
reach a certain level,

01:00:06.240 --> 01:00:09.870
they tend to sort of wind up
acting just like the people

01:00:09.870 --> 01:00:11.600
who were there before.

01:00:11.600 --> 01:00:14.230
So, there are dividends to
be paid on the front side.

01:00:14.230 --> 01:00:18.590
I think for recruiting of more
diverse crop of candidates

01:00:18.590 --> 01:00:21.620
to run for office, and it might
be that there will be dividends

01:00:21.620 --> 01:00:24.000
to pay in politicking
and management

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:26.160
of politics in the long run.

01:00:26.160 --> 01:00:29.230
How exactly we observe that
in policy is a little bit more

01:00:29.230 --> 01:00:32.060
abstract, I think.

01:00:32.060 --> 01:00:33.600
&gt;&gt; Seth Masket: Hey Julie.

01:00:33.600 --> 01:00:39.840
So, check me if I'm wrong here,
but I think women tend to be,

01:00:39.840 --> 01:00:43.740
within both parties, women tend
to be more liberal than men.

01:00:43.740 --> 01:00:45.920
You know, both within
their republican

01:00:45.920 --> 01:00:49.350
and within the democratic
parties.

01:00:49.350 --> 01:00:51.750
And so, you know,
that, you know,

01:00:51.750 --> 01:00:54.700
as their numbers increase
among elected officials,

01:00:54.700 --> 01:00:58.110
that tends to suggest
it will somewhat change.

01:00:58.110 --> 01:01:01.750
It could end up making the
republican party more moderate.

01:01:01.750 --> 01:01:04.110
It could end up making the
democratic party more liberal.

01:01:04.110 --> 01:01:07.540
And interestingly, it's not
just on thing, it's not even

01:01:07.540 --> 01:01:09.980
on things like reproductive
rights,

01:01:09.980 --> 01:01:11.280
where actually women's views

01:01:11.280 --> 01:01:12.930
and men's views are very
similar it turns out.

01:01:12.930 --> 01:01:15.480
But on just sort of
general economic issues,

01:01:15.480 --> 01:01:17.880
on general social
welfare issues.

01:01:17.880 --> 01:01:19.990
That could have the effect

01:01:19.990 --> 01:01:22.320
of moving the system
somewhat to the left.

01:01:22.320 --> 01:01:25.040
Now, it depends where these
women are getting electing.

01:01:25.040 --> 01:01:29.290
My understanding is most of
them are running as democrats.

01:01:29.290 --> 01:01:32.600
Most of the women
who are running

01:01:32.600 --> 01:01:34.510
for Congress right now
are running as democrats.

01:01:34.510 --> 01:01:36.610
So that'll probably
have a greater effect

01:01:36.610 --> 01:01:38.680
on the democratic party than
on the republican right now.

01:01:38.680 --> 01:01:40.770
But yeah, we could
see a different effect

01:01:40.770 --> 01:01:42.800
across both parties.

